properties.description: A short but tough opening hole. A lengthy bunker and O.B. protect the right side with native grasses and mounds protecting the left side. Requires a cautious approach to the green since it slopes away from you.
A lengthy par 4 that can play like a par 5. The tee shot must avoid O.B. and fairway bunkers on the right. The approach shot must negotiate a waste area on the left. Don’t overshoot the green here.

A relatively short par 5 that is a great birdie opportunity. Favor the right side of the fairway off the tee. Lay up to the left to leave a short approach or go for the green with a long iron or fairway utility. The green is undulating so keep an eye on the daily pin position.
A tricky par 4 that requires a tee shot in the fairway left of center. The approach is to a small two-tiered green so accuracy is a premium on this hole.
A short par 4 that doesn’t require a driver off the tee, but puts a premium on accuracy. Get it in the fairway and you have a short approach to a very generous green that is guarded by bunkers.

A long par 4 playing downhill into the prevailing wind off of Reeds Bay. The tee shot should favor the right center of the fairway. The approach shot is played to a pronounced two-tiered green with bunkers and the bay protecting any errant shots.
This lengthy par 3 plays uphill and is much harder than it appears. An accurate tee shot is a must to this well guarded green to the right, left and rear of the green.

A short par 4 requiring an accurate tee shot to the right center of the fairway. Marshland guards the right side and behind the green. The approach shot is delicate to an elevated green that slopes from front to back.
Deep bunkers await every shot and the green slopes severely to the back right.

This relatively short dog leg par 4 requires an accurate tee shot to the right center of the fairway. The smallest green on the course is partially blocked by grass mounding and bunkers that protect the green.
A long and difficult par 3 that plays into the prevailing wind may require a wood off the tee. Bunkers guard the right and left side of this generous green.

A sharp dog leg to the right that does not require a driver off the tee. Place an accurate tee shot in the left center of the fairway for the best angle into the green. The approach must be accurate to this elevated narrow green that slopes back to front.
Place your tee shot to the right center of the fairway for the best angle into the green. There is a ridge running the length of the undulating green so keep an eye on the daily pin position.

Requires an accurate tee shot to the right center of the fairway. The downhill approach shot is into the prevailing wind, so don’t be fooled by the distance. The green is guarded by bunkers and Reeds Bay.

This tough par 3 plays uphill to an elevated green that is generous in size. Threatened by a deep bunker on the left and marshland on the right, your tee shot must be accurate to a sloping back-to-front green.
This dog leg to the right can be a risk reward hole for the long hitters. Take your chances over the right bunker and leave yourself a short approach to this undulating green.
This well-guarded par 3 will test anyone’s wedge game. Playing 119 yards, it requires an accurate tee shot to a slightly elevated green.

This par 5 finishing hole is a good birdie opportunity. Fairway bunkers and O.B. await tee shots to the right with fairway bunkers guarding the left side. The second shot and the approach must avoid the bunkers and grass mounds to reach a green that slopes from front to back.
